        "text": "who was the chief.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The expression ‘the chief to begin the thanksgiving in prayer’ is not very intelligible. The Hebrew for ‘the chief to begin’ is literally ‘the head of the beginning (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "t’khillah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") who used to give thanks to the prayer’ i.e. after it. The LXX. and Vulg. Vss. follow a text, which differs in one letter, ‘the head of the praise’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "t’hillah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and gives a good sense, viz. ‘the head or leader of praise, one who gave thanks in the time of prayer,’ (LXX. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἄρχων τοῦ αἴνου καὶ Ἰούδας τῆς προσευχῆς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Vulg. ‘princeps ad laudandum et ad confitendum in oratione.’) But the obscurity of the Hebrew phrase probably arises from its having been a technical title of the leader of the Temple choir, a choregus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Bakbukiah the second among his brethren",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i.e. second to Mattaniah. Bakbukiah probably corresponds to Bakbakkar in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 9:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or to Berechiah in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Abda",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This name appears with the same genealogy as Obadiah in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "From the mention of ‘Asaph’ and ‘Jeduthun’ we evidently have in these verses (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 9:14-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the class of Levites, who, e.g. in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 2:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", stand before ‘the porters,’ i.e. ‘the singers.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
